The Australian National University (ANU) continues to attract thousands of international students each year, drawn by its strong academic reputation and vibrant campus life. However, the 2026 academic cycle has seen significant **student visa processing delays** affecting enrolments across Australian universities. According to the Department of Home Affairs' latest quarterly report, average processing times for subclass 500 visas from high-volume countries increased by 34% compared to early 2025, with some applications taking over 90 days to finalise. ANU's International Student Support team reported a 41% rise in **visa-related enrolment deferral requests** during the first quarter of 2026 alone. These delays create anxiety around maintaining active enrolment status and meeting the conditions of a Confirmation of Enrolment (CoE). This article explains how to navigate **ANU CoE extension requests**, stay enrolled while waiting, and access university support services designed for exactly this situation.

## Understanding the 2026 Visa Processing Landscape at ANU

The **ANU visa processing backlog** stems from a combination of factors that intensified throughout 2025 and into 2026. The Department of Home Affairs introduced enhanced integrity measures for student visa applications, including more rigorous Genuine Temporary Entrant (GTE) assessments and financial capacity checks. While these changes aim to strengthen the visa system, they have extended processing timelines substantially. Data from ANU's admissions office indicates that students from South Asia and parts of Southeast Asia are experiencing the longest wait periods, with median processing times reaching **68 days in early 2026** compared to 42 days in 2024. **High-risk assessment cohorts** face additional scrutiny, sometimes resulting in requests for further documentation that add weeks to the process. ANU has responded by increasing staffing in its International Student Compliance team and creating dedicated case management pathways for students whose visas remain pending beyond the standard enrolment deadline. Understanding this context helps students plan realistic timelines and recognise that **ANU visa processing delays are systemic**, not individual failures.

## The Critical Role of Your Confirmation of Enrolment

A **Confirmation of Enrolment (CoE)** is the foundational document for every international student at ANU. It serves as proof that you have accepted an offer and paid the required deposit, and it is essential for lodging a valid student visa application. Each CoE carries a specific course start date and an expiry date, typically aligned with the expected duration of your program plus a short wrap-up period. When **ANU visa processing delays** push beyond the CoE start date, the document becomes a point of vulnerability. If a student cannot commence by the CoE start date and has not received a visa, the CoE may become invalid, potentially triggering a cascade of compliance issues. ANU's policy in 2026 allows for **CoE start date adjustments** under defined circumstances, but these are not automatic. Students must actively monitor their CoE status through the ANU ISIS portal and respond promptly to any notifications. The university's International Student Advisers emphasise that **letting a CoE lapse without communication** is one of the most common and avoidable causes of enrolment cancellation.

## How to Request an ANU CoE Extension

The **ANU CoE extension process** requires timely action and clear communication with the university. If your visa has not been granted and your current CoE start date is approaching or has passed, follow these steps. First, log into your ANU applicant portal and check the status of your CoE. If the start date has elapsed, the system will typically flag your record for review. Contact the **ANU Admissions Office** directly via the international admissions enquiry form, selecting "CoE and Visa Issues" as the subject category. In your message, include your ANU student ID, the date you lodged your visa application, your Department of Home Affairs transaction reference number, and a brief explanation that you wish to request a **CoE start date extension due to ongoing visa processing**. ANU generally requires evidence that you have a pending visa application, so attach a screenshot of your ImmiAccount application status page. The admissions team will assess whether your program still has capacity for a later start and whether the delay falls within acceptable parameters. In most cases, ANU can issue a **revised CoE with a new start date** within 5 to 10 business days, though complex cases may take longer. There is no fee for a standard CoE extension, but repeated requests may attract administrative charges.

## Maintaining Enrolment Status During the Visa Wait

While waiting for a visa decision, your **ANU enrolment status during visa wait** periods depends on proactive engagement with university systems. ANU distinguishes between "deferred" and "active" enrolment statuses. If you have not yet arrived in Australia and your CoE start date passes without a visa grant, your enrolment may shift to a **conditional deferred status**. This means your place in the program is held, but you are not considered an actively enrolled student for that semester. The risk here is that prolonged deferral can affect your ability to complete the program within the original CoE timeframe, which may have implications for future visa applications. To avoid this, ANU recommends that students in visa limbo request a **formal deferral to the next available intake** as soon as it becomes clear they cannot commence on time. This keeps the CoE valid and aligned with a realistic start date. For students who have already arrived in Australia on a different visa and are awaiting a student visa grant, the rules are stricter. You must not commence studies until the student visa is granted, and you must maintain compliance with your current visa conditions. The **ANU Student Compliance Office** can provide individualised advice for these complex bridging visa scenarios.

## ANU Support Services for Visa-Delayed Students

ANU has strengthened its support infrastructure in response to the 2026 processing environment. The **ANU International Student Support team** offers dedicated visa delay assistance, including one-on-one consultations to review your case and recommend next steps. They can help you draft communications to the Department of Home Affairs, interpret requests for further information, and liaise with academic colleges on your behalf. Additionally, the **ANU Student Wellbeing and Safety unit** provides free counselling services for students experiencing stress or anxiety related to visa uncertainty. These services are available remotely, so you can access them even if you are still overseas. ANU has also established a **Visa Delay Communication Hub** on its website, which aggregates the latest processing time data, policy updates, and FAQs. The university's **ANU Legal Service** can offer preliminary advice on visa matters, though complex immigration cases may require a registered migration agent. Importantly, ANU does not charge international students for these support services; they are funded through the Student Services and Amenities Fee. Early engagement with these resources significantly improves outcomes, as advisers can intervene before enrolment deadlines harden into cancellations.

## Planning Your Timeline: Key Dates and Decision Points

Effective management of **ANU visa processing delays** requires a clear timeline with defined decision points. For Semester 1 2026, ANU set the standard **enrolment deadline at 28 February 2026**, with a late enrolment grace period extending to 14 March 2026 for students with pending visas. If your visa was still not granted by the grace deadline, the university required a formal deferral request or a CoE extension application. For Semester 2 2026, the standard enrolment deadline is 31 July 2026, with a similar grace period likely to apply. Students should mark **45 days before the CoE start date** as a checkpoint: if no visa decision has been received by that point, initiate contact with ANU admissions. At **21 days before the start date**, if there is still no update, request a CoE extension or deferral formally. These internal deadlines exist because ANU must report enrolment data to the Department of Home Affairs and manage course capacities. Missing them without communication can result in a **CoE cancellation**, which in turn may lead to visa refusal. ANU's published academic calendar for 2026 includes all relevant census dates and withdrawal deadlines, which also affect your enrolment status and financial liability.

## What Happens If Your Visa Is Refused After a CoE Extension

A **visa refusal** after a CoE extension creates a different set of challenges. If the Department of Home Affairs refuses your student visa application, ANU is typically notified through the Provider Registration and International Student Management System (PRISMS). The university will then cancel your CoE, as the document is only valid when linked to an active visa application or grant. At this point, your **enrolment status at ANU** becomes inactive, and any tuition fees paid may be subject to the university's refund policy. ANU's standard refund policy for international students allows for a full refund of tuition fees if the visa is refused, minus a small administrative fee, provided you supply the official refusal notice within a specified timeframe. You have the option to appeal the visa refusal through the Administrative Appeals Tribunal, but this is a legal process that requires careful consideration and often professional migration advice. ANU's International Student Advisers can explain the implications of a refusal and discuss whether a new application for a future intake is viable. In some cases, students may choose to reapply with strengthened documentation. The key is to act quickly: **visa refusal triggers** have strict timelines for both refund requests and appeals.

## FAQ

**How long does it take ANU to process a CoE extension request in 2026?**
The **ANU CoE extension process** typically takes between 5 and 10 business days for straightforward cases. Complex requests involving program capacity issues or repeated extensions may require up to 15 business days. ANU advises submitting extension requests at least 3 weeks before your current CoE start date to allow adequate processing time.

**Can I begin my ANU course online while waiting for my student visa?**
No. Under the **Education Services for Overseas Students Act 2000**, international students must hold a valid student visa to commence studies at an Australian university. ANU does not permit online commencement from overseas as a workaround for **ANU visa processing delays**. You must wait for the visa grant before enrolling in subjects.

**What happens if my ANU CoE expires before my visa is granted?**
If your CoE expires without a visa grant, ANU will cancel the CoE in PRISMS, which may lead to visa refusal. To prevent this, you must request a **CoE extension or deferral** before the expiry date. ANU's International Student Compliance team monitors expiring CoEs and typically sends reminder emails 14 days and 7 days before expiry.

**Are there any fees for ANU CoE extensions due to visa delays?**
The first **CoE extension request** related to visa processing delays is generally processed without a fee. Subsequent requests may incur an administrative charge of AUD 150, subject to review by the admissions team. This fee is waived in cases where the delay is clearly attributable to Department of Home Affairs processing backlogs.

